What is CIDR?

CIDR defines the IP address range available inside a VPC or subnet.

It tells AWS:

👉 How many machines (servers, databases, services) your network can support.

🧠 Example CIDR
10.0.0.0/16

This is called a CIDR Block.

✅ Meaning of 10.0.0.0/16

CIDR has two parts:

IP Address      Network Size
10.0.0.0        /16
Part 1 — Network Address (10.0.0.0)

This is the starting address of your private network.

AWS private IP ranges:

10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255
172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255
192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255

These are private networks (not accessible from internet).

Part 2 — /16 (Subnet Mask)

/16 tells:

👉 First 16 bits are fixed for network
👉 Remaining bits are available for hosts.

🔢 How Many IP Addresses?

Formula:

2^(32 - subnet bits)

For /16:

2^(32-16) = 65,536 IP addresses

So:

10.0.0.0 → 10.0.255.255

Your VPC can host ~65K resources.

✅ Common CIDR Sizes
CIDR	IP Addresses	Usage
/16	65,536	VPC
/24	256	Subnet
/28	16	Small subnet
🏗 Example VPC Design
VPC CIDR → 10.0.0.0/16

Subnets:
10.0.1.0/24  → Public Subnet
10.0.2.0/24  → Private Subnet
10.0.3.0/24  → Database Subnet
